<subSubSection pageId="77" pageNumber="78" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="77.[151,1436,655,861]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
Because this species was described by O. M. Reuter, author thinks its location within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carayon" authorityYear="1972" box="[1263,1414,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lasiochilinae">Lasiochilinae</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carayon" authorityYear="1972" box="[151,285,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lasiochilini">Lasiochilini</taxonomicName>
is reliable, but its generic placement is uncertain. The original description is very brief and important diagnostic character states were not mentioned. Author highlights only two of them: the longitudinal groove marked on the pronotum, a character present in a few species of different genera, and the forefemora slightly enlarged, a characteristic rare among 
<emphasis box="[570,659,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter, 1871" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" box="[570,655,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Dilasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hemiptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dilasia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the genus in which, author supposes, it should be.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
